9. FURTHER RESEARCH

In a way, it is remarkable that the semantic category of FD escaped notice until the present line of work, given the attention to concepts of force outside linguistics and their pervasiveness within language. Once recognized, however, it is widely evident, and in fact must be acknowledged as one of the preeminent conceptual organizing categories in language. Thus, we have seen here that the linguistic force-dynamic system operates in a common way over the physical, psychological, social, inferential, discourse, and mentalmodel domains of reference and conception. As a system, FD warrants much additional investigation, and I suggest now several lines of further research.
While a number of parameters of the FD system have been presented during the exposition, still further distinctions appear to play a role. In (54) are summarized many of the distinctions we noted, and the final three name additional possibilities. The first of these, (54p), pertains to whether a forceexerting entity is spatially localized or distributed. While localized cases dominated in the examples, the ‘stiff grass’ of (3~) is an Antagonist manifesting its force effect distributively. The next parameter, (54q), contrasts the uniform exertion of a force with an exertion gradient. One form of gradient is the ‘rubber band’ type, in which the further an Agonist or Antagonist is pushed from its home position, the greater its resistance or force toward return. And parameter (54r) distinguishes the predominant pushing form of force exertion, the only type considered in this paper, from the pulling form, which is evident in locutions like attract. It is clear that additional work on linguistic FD will yield still further parameters, as well as an amplified system within which the parameters interrelate.

